y Pink Moth and The Smack It is Way.',NULL,NULL),(68037,38498,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2019/10/31/CFR Booo! - October 31, 2019 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2019-10-31 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-14 21:48:58',NULL,'This episode of CFRU Boo is all about the music, and it\'s all about a place called the Homewood sanitarium, which opened in 1883 and was used to treat people who were disturbed by the supernatural. Since its inception, patients have flocked to the hospital for experimental electroshock treatments. Many patients complain of headaches and hallucinations, but the medical community has been impressed with the success of the treatment. The patients are cast into a basement deep in the bowels of the hospital, left to stew in their agony within their minds.\n\nMany cry, some say on a clear night. The first song on the program is \"Big Black Death\" off of the album \"The Singing from Mount erie\" by local artist Cots. The second song is \"Cotts\" from the album, \"The Song from Mount Erie\" by Pooch Yates. The third song is from \"Evan Gordon\'s Haunted History of Guelph\" about a \"haunted kind of ghostwalk\" we had with Evan a few years back. The fourth song is a \"horrible soul\" singing their last song. The fifth song is the live version of \"Cots\" by the local artist, Pooch. The live version is \"',NULL,NULL),(68038,38498,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2019/10/31/CFR Booo! - October 31, 2019 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2019-10-31 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-14 21:35:06',NULL,'This week on the program, Tom talks about the upcoming Guelph Film Festival. The festival is taking place from November 1 to 9th. He tells the listeners that they can listen to the program on their own devices and on the web. They can also make a donation to the festival. The program ends with a reminder that the festival is coming up on October 31st.',NULL,NULL),(68039,38498,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2018/10/31/CFR Booo! - October 31, 2018 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2018-10-31 20:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-14 21:20:03',NULL,'This week\'s program is a mix of news and music from the Guelph area. It begins with a brief announcement from the host of the station, who says that the program called CFRU Rhythm will not be airing tonight because of a technical issue. The program will instead be airing a rebroadcast that was originally airing earlier this year, Eternal Rhythm. The host also announces that the upcoming Guelph Film Festival will take place on November 2nd and 10th.',NULL,NULL),(68040,38498,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2017/10/31/CFRBooo! - October 31, 2017 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2017-10-31 19:00:00',86376576,'2023-11-14 19:10:16',NULL,'This program is a mix of news and music from the CFRU campus. The program begins with the announcement that the university has a power outage. The station is broadcasting via backup generators, but they are still doing their Boo show. The show\'s director, Christopher, explains that he had planned to come on at 6.35 but had to come early because of a power surge at the university.',NULL,NULL),(68041,38498,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2017/10/31/CFRBooo! - October 31, 2017 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2017-10-31 18:00:00',86376576,'2023-11-14 18:58:02',NULL,'Welcome back, we\'re back on the streets of Guelph, where we left off. Okay, so this is where it all started: the Underground Pit. Just outside of the city limits lies a mysterious sinkhole. The Ministry of Environment can\'t figure out what\'s going on, but it\'s causing all kinds of weird noises and sickness in the neighborhood.\n\nAround this same time last year a mom and daughter decided to climb into the pit to play a game. The kids heard weird noises, and some people even got sick from the pit. Now we find out that this is the same place where the underground pit used to be, the Homewood Sanatorium. It\'s where people from all over the world go to undergo electroshock therapy. Unfortunately, these people don\'t like it, and they end up in the basement of the Sanatorium with all the pain and suffering. The story of the underground hospital is just one of many stories of people suffering and dying from their own misfortunes.',NULL,NULL),(68042,38498,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2017/10/31/CFRBooo! - October 31, 2017 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2017-10-31 17:00:00',86376576,'2023-11-14 18:42:01',NULL,'The second edition of the Secret Scope program opens with a description of the music on the program. It\'s a collection of progressive rock and alternative music from the Prague- and Alt-sounds. The music opens with the music from a children\'s game called Ned, which was released in 1997.\n\nThe music in this program comes from an upcoming quadruple listening set, which includes a new album from a Victoria artist named Rained a ton, an album from Brian Eno, a folk album from Philadelphia called Shadow band with Shadow Land, and a psychedelic rock album from Blood Ceremony. The program closes with the instrumental music from Maria Zuda\'s solo project, Lunatic soul.',NULL,NULL),(68043,38498,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2017/10/31/CFRBooo! - October 31, 2017 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2017-10-31 13:00:00',86376576,'2023-11-14 17:02:17',NULL,'The show opens with the theme of \"spooky\" and the song \"Goli Mar\" is a song from a movie about an actor called Chiranjeevi.\n\nThe song is from the movie \"Donga\" and it is from a song called \"Gol Mar\" by the singer. After the song is over, the group discusses the holiday of Halloween and its significance to them. The group discusses music and its importance to the holiday, and the songs that have been played in the past day. They decide to start with \"Fresh Prince\" and \"Are You Ready For Freddy\" by Will Smith and the Fat Boys respectively. After \"Are you ready for Freddy,\" they will continue with \"Spooky Scary\" by Trey. He explains that he was \"wrong time\" to join the \"Wolfen Clan\" at his bar mitzvah.\n\nThe bar mitzvah was a success, but he was too busy to sing the song. He dances with his cousins and they had fun making \"circumcision jokes\" but then he remembers the song and remembers that the song was about a group of people who were all \"brain sucking pack\" and they were on the attack because they were \"all turned into zombies\" and were \"on the',NULL,NULL),(68044,38498,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2017/10/31/CFRBooo! - October 31, 2017 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2017-10-31 12:00:00',86376576,'2023-11-14 16:47:20',NULL,'This is the second part of a two-part interview with the host of the local music station, CFRU 95.3FM. The first part is about the upcoming Guelph Film Festival that\'s coming up in a few days. The host explains that the festival is for people interested in issues such as social justice, community building, and the environment. The second part is a little bit more personal. The show is going to take listeners back to the days of the jungle, when jungle music was more popular than today\'s alternative music.\n\nThe jungle music that the host is playing is actually one of the tracks from an album called Unified Colors, which was released in 1994. The show goes on to explain that the music is being played because it\'s lonely and lonely out in the cold and dark. The night sky is full of dark clouds and all kinds of things are lurking around you. The house where the show is taking place seems to be very scary. The only thing that seems to make the house more scary is the fact that there\'s electricity in the house. The music is playing because the house has some kind of power. This is because the place you\'re in seems to have some sort of power source. So you',NULL,NULL),(68054,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/31/Democracy Now - October 31, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-31 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-14 16:30:40',NULL,'The war in the Gaza Strip continues, and the death toll has reached 8,500. As the war continues, the United Nations Childrens Agency warns that Israel is committing \"rampant grave violations\" of children\'s rights.\n\nThe agency\'s director-general warns that over 8,500 children have been killed in the last 26 days, most of them women and children. In the aftermath of the latest attacks, the Israeli military has pushed deeper into the besieged territory. The Israeli Prime Minister, Benjamin Netanyahu, has refused to agree on a ceasefire. He says that calls for Israel\'s surrender to Hamas are just calls for the surrender of Israel to terrorism. In response, Hamas has released a prisoner video showing three women held captive by the military wing of the Islamic militant group. The release of the women is a sign that Israel has freed one of the captives, Ori Megadish. The death of Shani Luke is also a sign of the end of the war.',NULL,NULL),(68055,38498,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/31/CFR Booo! - October 31, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-31 12:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-14 16:20:36',NULL,'This is the first time Jenny has been involved with the festival, and she is very excited. She is also excited because she has been part of the technology side of the event as well. She says that it is the busiest time of the year for her manager, Brian. They have a bunch of new volunteers this year, and they want to make sure that they are all up to speed on the latest technology.',NULL,NULL),(68065,38498,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/31/CFR Booo! - October 31, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-31 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-14 16:03:07',NULL,'In this chapter, we find out about the experiences of one of our students, who goes by the name of Dr. Brown. He was a medical student at the University of Nebraska Medical School. He had co-op at the medical school and was able to experience what medical procedures were and how they affected people.\n\nHe thinks it was a cool experience and that it encouraged him to go into medicine. Dr Brown notes that he thinks universities take into account the amount of experience students have at co-ops, but he doesn\'t know if they actually do. He does know that he got good recommendations for co-operation from the people at the school. He also thinks it\'s a good way to gain conflict resolution and understanding of people.\n\nEven if it didn\'t contribute to his degree, he still benefited from the co-operative experience. He says he never did coop in his high school but he did a ton of extracurriculars at school. The professors told him that if he were going into a particularly competitive school and there were lots of applicants and good grades, then things that separated students would be helpful, like co-curricular experiences. He adds that he did not get the best grades in his class, but that',NULL,NULL),(68066,38498,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/31/CFR Booo! - October 31, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-31 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-14 15:45:12',NULL,'In this episode of the CFRU 9:20AM program, the students discuss the band Per with the station\'s host, and the students also discuss the Per\'s early days. The students began playing music together when they were in high school, and they met at a bullring in the spring of last year.\n\nThey liked the opportunity to play together, and decided to keep playing. As the school year progressed, they spent more time together and the summer passed. Per says that they\'re back in full swing now, and that they plan to continue to play in the future. They\'re still a band, however, and have a sense of humor, which keeps them together.',NULL,NULL),(68076,1453,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/10/31/Silver Screen Dream Machine - October 31, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-10-31 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-14 15:29:20',NULL,'On this special edition of Dream Machine, we hear music from a variety of animated and live-action films. The first song we hear is the opening song from a 1993 stop-motion animated film called Before Christmas