g to be accompanied by some other people, like Curtis Harding, Owen Watt, and Shemekia, who are all going to perform. Then the show ends with a shout-out to the community. The program is hosted by CFRU\'s Campus Community and Media Center. The CFRU team plays the best music from around the city. They also host community outreach events and festivals. The team needs people to be the face of the community at these events. They need volunteers to help with the booth, to record public service announcements, and to write ads. The whole thing is very flexible. The show concludes with a quote from the program that sums up the vibe of the program: \"Every Wednesday morning here at CFRU,the stillness in the dance brings you sound local to the core.\"',NULL,NULL),(69199,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/10/Democracy Now - November 10, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-10 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-10 22:15:26',NULL,'Israel\'s offensive on the Gaza Strip has reached a new high point, with the death toll approaching 11,000 people, including nearly 4,500 children. The White House has agreed to a six-hour humanitarian pause in the fighting in order to allow civilians in the northern part of the territory to flee. But the U. N. estimates that 50,000 people have been forced to travel along what Israel is calling a \"humanitarian corridor\" to escape the fighting. Craig Maciber, the former U.N\'s top human rights officer, condemns the humanitarian corridors as \"mere ethnic cleansing\" and says they are a \"cruel and cynical charade\" for the perpetrators to be held accountable. The Pentagon reports that two U. S. fighter planes have attacked an ammunition depot in eastern Syria. The strikes follow a series of aerial attacks on American troops in the Middle East and North Africa. The top relief official from the United Nations warns that the current conflict in the region is \"a wildfire\" that could \"spread\" and that it may lead to \"a much wider war\" across the region.',NULL,NULL),(69200,3686,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/10/Volunteer Playlist - November 10, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-10 12:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-10 22:04:29',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(69201,126,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/10/Viejoteca - November 10, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-10 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-10 21:06:39',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(69202,126,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/10/Viejoteca - November 10, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-10 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-10 21:06:39',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(69208,127,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/10/LiYghTE FM - November 10, 2023 at 16:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-10 16:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-11 14:17:53',NULL,'This is a music video that was recorded by the creator of the music program, DJ Double D. It is the first music video in the history of the program. It was recorded on the day of the Super Bowl. It takes place on the eve of the season. The music is all about the love revolution. The song is called \"The View\" by an artist named Tori Y Ma, who has released an EP called \"Sand Hills.\" The show ends with a shout-out to all of the people who have been listening to the program this week.',NULL,NULL),(69209,1620,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/10/Hellfire Radio - November 10, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-10 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-12 20:10:01',NULL,'The Hellfire Radio guys talk about the weather, how it\'s starting to change, and how Saxon is looking a bit \"ghosty and toasty\" today. Before they start talking about music, they mention that they just heard a song from Bri Webb\'s new album \"Run With Me\" Thunder Bay. Before that, they heard \"Splay of Decay\" The Butcher. The guys say they haven\'t yet heard that one, but they\'ll hear it soon. Then, they\'re talking about some other music they\'ve heard recently. They mention that one of their old metal clubmates is now in town, and he used to play the Saxon band on his underground rock roller, so maybe they should check out their discography.',NULL,NULL),(69211,128,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/10/Walkuman Style - November 10, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-10 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-11 14:00:51',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(69212,135,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/10/Folk Roots Radio - November 10, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-10 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-11 13:52:12',NULL,'This week on the program, we hear from Graham and Scott, a traveling folk duo known as the Ruffin\'s and Tumble. They\'ve released a new album and they\'re happy to have a home to call their own. We also hear from Joe Crookston, who\'s releasing a new nine-song EP, Looking for Yes; Katie Dahl, who has a new seven-song album out; and Don Ross, who just released his latest album Water. We wrap up the program with more music from the upcoming week, including the single Ain\'t that the way from the new album by the traveling duo.',NULL,NULL),(69213,129,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/10/Digital Statik - November 10, 2023 at 19:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-10 19:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-11 13:38:23',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(69214,3686,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/10/Volunteer Playlist - November 10, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-10 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-11 13:27:41',NULL,'At the annual launch of Black History Month, Sarah S. A. R.-A.H., the vice-president of student affairs at the university, begins by acknowledging the university\'s connection to the land and to the people who live there. She then launches into a brief history of Black history in Canada, specifically the history of slavery in the United States from the 1600 to the American Revolution. Black people have lived in Canada for generations, and the number of Black Canadians has grown.',NULL,NULL),(69215,132,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/10/Global Rare Grooves - November 10, 2023 at 21:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-10 21:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-11 13:00:49',NULL,'This week\'s episode of the Looking Glass opens with a description of the blocking of news content by Facebook and Instagram as a result of Bill C-18. The University of Guelph\'s campus and community news is still being shared, but due to the blocking, it\'s no longer possible to find it on Facebook or on Instagram. If you want to continue to support the university, you can sign up for the university\'s newsletter at . ./CFRU slash newsletter. The Member of Parliament for Guelph, Lloyd Longfield, is also involved in this fight, and he\'ll be able to help.',NULL,NULL),(69216,1491,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/10/Industry Tactics - November 10, 2023 at 22:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-10 22:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-11 13:15:26',NULL,'This episode is called \"Industry Tactics\" and it\'s all about the music industry. In this episode, we find out that the person we\'re talking to is Annalise Naron. She\'s a music pioneer, a role model, and a pioneer in the Canadian music scene. Annalise has a lot to tell us about her life and career. She has an incredible story to tell, and she\'s super stoked to be a part of this. She and her friend, Teleborg, had a lot of fun playing music together. The two of them are now totally BFFs. As they\'re chatting, Annalise mentions that she used to work at Honest Eds, where she and Selena Martin played a lot. She was also a member of the band that played at the House Cameron with Doug Friesen, Jesse Baird, and Gunku. The conversation turns to Annalise\'s guitar playing. She says that it left a mark on her when she first started playing music, and that\'s why she loves it so much.','fix',NULL),(69217,1491,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/10/Industry Tactics - November 10, 2023 at 23:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-10 23:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-11 12:22:58',NULL,'The first song is a big hit, but it\'s a long way off from being a successful song. When the song\'s finished, the song is still a work in progress. The next song is even better, but this time, it\'ll be a song about navigating the social aspects of writing a song. The song is awesome, but the lyrics are too dumb for the social context of writing. That\'s one of the things that makes the song so awesome. The other goal that you had was to engineer Juno Records, just to be considered an engineer. That goal doesn\'t happen to you, though, because you don\'t have a ton of records to work on. So, you know... Juno Records? Yeah, that sounds a lot like the dumb goal. But then again, Juno Records isn\'t a lot of work for other artists. Plus, Juno\'s the only music industry where women aren\'t represented. So if you\'re a female engineer, you can\'t just go to Juno and get a job there. You have to work for a lot more money to get a good job. And then you\'ve got to compete with male engineers for a bunch of other',NULL,NULL),(69218,1627,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/11/Jitterbuggin - November 11, 2023 at 00:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-11 00:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-11 12:11:45',NULL,'Welcome to the show, and welcome to CFRU. We\'re going to have to admit that we\'re a little surprised to hear this, because we\'ve never heard the show before. So, first off, the show is called \"Sunday Morning.\" It\'s pre-recorded, which means that the DJ is out in his home studio talking to himself and his guests. The show is not really a live show; it\'s just a prerecorded show. The DJ explains that he has a pre-set time for the show and a picture of his desktop, his laptop, or his TV. He can tell you how long it will take him to get to the studio. He says that if he assumes that his program coordinator, Chris, has already hit the show at midnight, then everything will be perfect. The reason he\'s doing this is because everyone in the house is asleep, and there\'s no one to play music to. The only reason he does it is because he likes to listen to the other guests and to hear their voices. He doesn\'t care if they\'re asleep or not. He just wants to be a part of the fun.',NULL,NULL),(69234,136,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/11/A Dog’s Breakfast - November 11, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-11 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-11 22:48:27',NULL,'The program opens with a toast to all of the music and dance acts that have played at the party. The group then moves on to a new track, a song by a Canadian band called the Minor Empire. The band is composed of musicians from the Turkish-Canadian community. They play music from the uprooted world of their homeland. The narrator says that he\'s a \"mysterious Toronto-based group\" and he loves the sound of this band\'s music. They\'re also going to play a gig in Calgary with a local musician called Holly Blazina and a flamenco guitar player. The music on the CD they\'re playing is called \"oblation\" from \"transcendental\" . The DJ says it\'s hard to tell, but it sounds like there are a lot of people in the music. He\'s not sure how to explain it to the listeners, but he thinks they\'ll like it. He says he\'ll try to explain this to the audience.',NULL,NULL),(69235,1344,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/11/Beautiful Druid - November 11, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-11 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-11 22:31:19',NULL,'The show is called Beautiful Druid and it is hosted by Alden Hadwin. He tells us that he will be introducing music. He will try to tell you who composed the songs as well as the people who performed them. The first song he will play is called The Final Goodbye by Roger Whitaker. He then plays a song written by Ron Webster, who wrote the lyrics to the song. Then he plays a traditional song from Cape Breton called The Scotch Croquet. And finally he plays an English song called The Band Waltzing Matilda written by Eric Bozel. The band is from Scotland. The song is called Green Fields',NULL,NULL),(69237,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/11/Sound Magic - November 11, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-11 12:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-11 22:18:38',NULL,'Sound Magic is the name of the program on the CFRU 93.3.3 FM station in Guelph, Ontario, Canada. The program starts off with some music by a famous English composer named Sir Charles Villiers-Stanford. He was a symphonist, or teacher, in England. Stanford lived from 1852 until 1924 and wrote a piece for the end of World War I. This is one of the few recorded works of the war, and it deals with the death of hundreds of thousands of soldiers. The piece was written during a period of English history and English music when the British were trying to come up with a figure for the number of dead during the war. The Ulster Orchestra conducts Howard Shelley in the recording of the piece. Sound Magic goes back to some English music, and this time it\'s a little bit more German influence. It sounds like music from the mid-1800s. In other words, it sounds like rock \'n\' roll.',NULL,NULL),(69238,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/11/Sound Magic - November 11, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-11 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-12 05:41:43',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(69239,138,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/11/Sound Magic - November 11, 2023 at 13:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-11 13:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-11 22:02:28',NULL,'In this chapter, we\'re introduced to the music of British composer, William Bolingbroke, better known as \"Wong Williams.\" He\'s the most famous composer in the English music canon, and he\'s also one of the most popular and influential composers of the twentieth century. The piece that we\'ll be hearing this week is a large oracular cantata by Williams, written during the period of World War I and World War II. It\'s a patriotic piece about war and peace. It uses a number of quotations from famous poets like Walt Whitman and John Donne. It also uses some military imagery. The title of this piece is \"Agnus Dei\" from the Catholic mass, which basically means, \"Give us peace,\" or \"Have mercy on us,\" or whatever the Latin phrase for peace is. This is the first of many pieces that Williams wrote during this period. There are also other pieces in the piece, like \"Reconciliation,\" \"Dirge for Two Veterans,\" and \"Angel of Death.\" The final piece, \"O man, greatly loved, fear not,\" is a \"final benediction\" that promises that \"we will evolve beyond the war.\"',NULL,NULL),(69240,163,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/8zf7h2/November_11th_Critics_Circle62td1.mp3','2023-11-11 15:03:40',143961989,'2023-11-12 05:33:07',NULL,'Phil Taylor is back on the program, and he introduces us to a special guest: George F.Walker, a Canadian playwright who has been writing about marginalized people in the city. Phil describes Walker as a giant in the Canadian theater scene, having produced two plays per year. He is also a playwright of great influence in the world of television. Phil says that Walker \"champions\" certain groups of people, including the homeless, the police officers, and immigrants. He notes that Walker\'s plays are frequently performed elsewhere in Canada and that he cannot be arrested in Canada. Phil also discusses the importance of diversity in the arts in Canada, but he says that it\'s difficult to find plays by white, middle-aged men playwrights in Toronto. Phil goes on to say that the \"pretty unhappy culture\" in Canada is so unhappy that we\'re missing out on important people.',NULL,NULL),(69241,163,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/ubnxqf/November_4th_2023_Critic_s_Circlebjs75.mp3','2023-11-06 15:11:21',143961989,'2023-11-12 05:20:52',NULL,'This is the second of two parts in which we delve into the lives of two people who are doing their best to make tickets available to the public: Daniel Garber, the founder of Tickets.com, and Lynn Slotskins, a writer who writes about plays. The first part focuses on the complicated process of creating tickets, but the second part deals with a discussion of the recent baseball season in which the Texas Rangers defeated the Toronto Blue Jays in seven games. The second part discusses the significance of this season\'s play and the importance of blocked balls in Major League Baseball. The third part is devoted to discussing the city of Phoenix, where the plays are being produced, and the city\'s reputation as a baseball town.',NULL,NULL),(69242,167,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/vyx3q5/November_10th_2023_Funk_Fridays74jig.mp3','2023-11-10 21:45:37',431961989,'2023-11-12 05:09:15',NULL,'The Funky Fridays Nation thanks Stepney for his tribute to Richard Eisley. They\'re going to do a tribute to him, but they\'re also going to have a special three-hour segment dedicated to funk and soul music. So it\'s time for another edition of \"Funky Fridays.\" We\'re starting off with the music of Teddy Randazzo, who wrote \"Going Out of my Head Over You\" for Little Anthony\'s Black Vocal Quartet. Also, the music by Esther Phillips, who started out as a gospel singer and went on to become a jazz vocalist. She died in 1984 after an addiction to morphine. She was a talented singer, but she was also a drug addict. She had a smoky voice. So she\'s going to start the show with \"Going out of my head over you,\" which is an original song by Randazzo. Then she\'ll play \"Another Kind of Love,\" which was produced by Joe Beck and Dave Siamborn, then \"You\'re So Beautiful,\" which will be heard later in the show. And finally, \"Atom and the Justice\" will be played by Andrea Louise.',NULL,NULL),(69243,170,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/p7z73k/Ruby_Slippers_Nov_10C_mp3_-_2023-11-06_234_PM9ibpm.mp3','2023-11-10 22:50:09',111378520,'2023-11-12 04:54:35',NULL,'The next edition of Ruby Slippers is a mix of new releases from some of the underground acts in town. The first band is called The Velt and it\'s from Jerry Legrande\'s latest release Don Lance. The band will perform on November 29th at the TD Music Hall. The show will also be available on Mixcloud and the CIUT web site. The next show is all about supporting underground artists. This time, it is three artists: Missy Bauman, Old House, and Al Grantham, and Belly Up',NULL,NULL),(69244,175,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/89jk6y/November_9th_2023_No_Man_s_Land9vsxh.mp3','2023-11-10 21:51:07',283970176,'2023-11-12 04:41:43',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(69245,182,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/94ebji/NBR_Nov_8_2023_R8dnyz.mp3','2023-11-10 12:26:32',143195950,'2023-11-12 04:33:03',NULL,'On this week\'s show, the host reminds listeners that their membership slash campaign to raise money for a local radio station is underway. The station\'s goal is to raise $100,000. The host also announces that he\'ll be talking with a long-time musician named Nichole Crump, who was a member of the early noise scene in Toronto. The show starts with a performance by Ponto, who will be celebrating his 25th year in the business. Then it\'s a conversation with two other artists: Ramposide and Fresh Snow. Then the host announces an interview with Nichole\'s former bandmate, who is now known as Cupping no Cupping. Nichole was a bandmate in Disguises, which was a punk band that played a lot of punk-influenced music. She also played Roman Pilates and other things. She\'s got a new band called Sky Servant, which sounds a lot like her old band.',NULL,NULL),(69246,187,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/9mgzjr/DREAMING_-_EPISODE_NOVEMBER_10_2023bqwmj.mp3','2023-11-11 00:02:00',141067329,'2023-11-12 04:18:59',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(69247,186,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/s6ajae/November_9th_2023_Higher_Ground9dmsv.mp3','2023-11-10 21:47:58',287962512,'2023-11-12 04:05:56',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(69248,200,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/zi46w4/Karibuni_Nov5-23a0a4w.mp3','2023-11-06 05:33:22',287962512,'2023-11-12 19:55:58',NULL,'',NULL,NULL),(69249,207,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/f8iepq/Music_w_db_Hawkes_Nov_8_2023_Podcast9029g.mp3','2023-11-06 15:23:57',279799640,'2023-11-12 19:40:59',NULL