t provinces. The first hour is devoted to music from the off-center, and the two hours are devoted to a series of geographical spotlights.\n\nThe program starts with an announcement of the tracks they\'re playing. It\'ll be an announcement by the host of the show, and he\'s going to announce the first track that the band is going to hear. This will be a track from a new album by composer Linda-Kaitlyn Smith, with the name Dark Flower. This is her first album, and she\'s seen a lot of success with her work. Her music is very personal and experimental, and it\'s a lot like Anderson\'s music. The band is listening to the music on CFRU 93.3FM in Guelph, and they also have it available on Soundcloud.\n\nThe show begins with Sarah-Dilachy\'s long-form string quartet Long Gradus Part II. This track is one of three that the host has heard on the program. The other two tracks are from Josh-Josh Zubat\'s string quartet. The host says that he\'d like to',NULL,NULL),(69426,154,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/20/This Night Wounds Time - November 20, 2023 at 01:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-20 01:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-20 17:11:39','2023-11-20 09:07:17','This Night Wound\'s Time The show starts off with a geographical spotlight on music from Formosa province in Argentina.The artist is from that province, and there is only a limited amount of music from that area to choose from.So playing only one track from the artist is not an end in itself.The show then pauses for a brief break.\n\nThey will resume their program when they return.They ask listeners if they have something they are trying to fix, but don\'t know what\'s wrong with it.What if you have an art piece that you want to create but are unsure how to begin.Die Out, a community workshop that teaches people how to use tools and equipment, has moved to its new location and hosts weekly maker meetings on Monday nights from 8pm to 9pm.If you would like to tour the workshop or help with one of their community projects, they have a workshop at 700 York road every Monday night from 8:00pm to 9:00pm.\n\nWe invite you to join us on Sunday nights when we travel through the looking glass and follow the sounds wherever it takes us on the show.Alice tells us that the annual general meeting of the University of Guelph will be held on December 14th as a live and virtual',NULL,NULL),(69427,78,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/20/Morning Soul Shake-Up! - November 20, 2023 at 08:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-20 08:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-20 16:42:16','2023-11-20 15:05:59','',NULL,NULL),(69428,110,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/20/Here Today - November 20, 2023 at 07:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-20 07:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-20 16:37:53','2023-11-20 15:06:46','On this edition of the CFRU-FM program hosted by Aaron Badgley, the show opens with a conversation about the latest music from Jimmy Rankin, who is a member of the Rankin family. Aaron then discusses the latest song from the band Restraint, which is from their upcoming album Transience, and the latest single from the singer of the Christian Constantines, Bri Webb, who used to sing with Stephen Lamke.',NULL,NULL),(69429,175,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/krs3ri/November_16th_2023_No_Man_s_Landbc16g.mp3','2023-11-20 16:26:43',287962512,'2023-11-21 02:56:33','2023-11-20 17:05:27','The band gets ready to play some music for the 25th anniversary of No Man\'s Land. They\'re also planning a fall fundraiser to support the organization. Richard Medicineman wants to hear from everyone who has been a part of the music community in the past 25 years. He\'s asking people to send him an email. He also wants people to call the phone room. He needs volunteers to help him with the phone booth. Beef Farmer is taking the band on as well. Richard asks everyone to go to the charity site to make donations. It\'s so easy to do.',NULL,NULL),(69430,186,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/jz7pih/November_16th_2023_Higher_Ground6k6ep.mp3','2023-11-20 16:29:27',287962512,'2023-11-21 01:45:10','2023-11-20 17:05:37','The Higher Ground Show is a fundraiser for the community radio station, CIUT. Higher Ground is a show that mixes music from the great reverend Evo Taylor and other great artists.\n\nThe show is hosted by the station\'s founder and executive producer, David Macpherson. He has been doing the show for 25 years and feels that it is important for the listeners of the station. He tells listeners that the station relies on their support not the support of big corporations. He reminds listeners that CIUT is their home and that all the music on the show is from their community. He urges listeners to join the station and to give a bit of money so that the show can continue. \n\nIf you are just tuning in, the show invites you to come and support the station, which is located in the heart of the city. If you have not yet done so, please visit the station to make your contribution. You can pay by going to the website and clicking on the \"donate\" button on the top right hand corner. There, you will find a link to the show where you can pay for the show. The station hopes that listeners will continue to listen to it and support it',NULL,NULL),(69431,206,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/jb83n8/November_18th_2023_The_Minx_Sessionsazqmn.mp3','2023-11-20 15:54:59',287962512,'2023-11-20 23:04:09','2023-11-20 17:05:50','',NULL,NULL),(69432,216,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/5xusmv/RAW111723.mp3','2023-11-20 16:07:56',287962512,'2023-11-21 01:23:15','2023-11-20 17:05:53','',NULL,NULL),(69433,216,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/6ebq9v/RAW111023.mp3','2023-11-20 16:03:50',287962512,'2023-11-21 02:04:38','2023-11-20 17:05:54','',NULL,NULL),(69434,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/20/Breezy Breakfast Radio - November 20, 2023 at 10:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-20 10:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-20 17:52:55','2023-11-20 17:06:06','The city decides to buy land in the heritage conservation district, which is owned by the city, for a park. The city believes it will save money, but it will also benefit the community in many ways, such as it will be a great place to visit and to learn. The mayor says the city will have to sell the idea to the politicians, but he is excited about the new governance structure that Parks Canada has put in place. The new governance plan allows multiple owners to participate in the management of the park. First Nations can also be a part of the governance structure, even though they are not landowners.',NULL,NULL),(69435,79,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/20/Breezy Breakfast Radio - November 20, 2023 at 09:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-20 09:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-21 01:52:59','2023-11-20 17:06:06','Phil welcomes Brian Skerrett to the program. He explains that the former Reformatory is now a prison, but that he has been working on restoring it to its former glory. He says that he will be talking about some of the important artifacts that are on the property, and that he would like to take the guests on a tour of the property. Phil says that they are guests at the prison, so they should reflect on their privilege to live in the city, and the responsibility they have to care for the land.\n\nHe also says that, while they would like for peace to be broken out once and all, they also desire peace for others. Phil thanks Brian for coming, and says he\'s now with the new Urban Park Guelph, which is the name for the new national urban park in Guelph. When asked why the word \"national\" isn\'t in the title of the new park, Phil says it depends on who is asking.If someone asks why, he says, there are too many syllables, and if they ask someone else, he points out that if they decide not to call the park a national park but want a park nonetheless, it gives them a lot of freedom.','fix',NULL),(69436,1437,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/20/Democracy Now - November 20, 2023 at 11:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-20 11:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-20 19:46:41','2023-11-20 19:07:49','The war in Gaza has reached a crisis point, according to a new report from the United Nations Relief and Works Agency for Palestine Refugees in the Near East. At least 13,000 Palestinians have been killed in the conflict, and the number of wounded has nearly doubled. The report also points to the death of an Israeli peace activist, Vivian Silver, whose remains have been identified. The war will not bring peace, says the report, and it is time for the world to stop being taught that war will bring about peace.',NULL,NULL),(69437,1438,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/20/Worst Responders - November 20, 2023 at 12:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-20 12:00:00',86638720,'2023-11-20 19:27:05','2023-11-20 19:07:50','This is a very short and very funny comedy show. It is called Worst Responders and it is about two stand up comedians dealing with problems that people have on the internet. It starts off with two students, Charissa and Renee, who talk about how they are currently mid-October and how they think that September is crazy. They discuss how they used to be able to communicate with each other but now it\'s much more difficult because of the way that they use the internet and their inability to communicate using words like \"chat\" and \"chat. The students also discuss the upcoming reading week at the university and how it is not a good idea because they want to end their term early.',NULL,NULL),(69438,80,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/20/CFRU Playlist - November 20, 2023 at 14:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-20 14:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-20 21:06:16','2023-11-20 21:06:16',NULL,NULL,NULL),(69439,174,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/ux2ggb/November_15_2023_Global_Rhythms94rc7.mp3','2023-11-20 21:15:49',431961989,'2023-11-21 01:47:42','2023-11-20 23:05:22','Ken Stowar, the founder and president of the Rhythm Club, gives a speech on the history of the club and its mission. He talks about how the club was founded and how its members came to be. He also talks about his father and his grandfather who were influential in the club\'s history.\n\nKen says that his grandfather was a very important man, and he is proud of his family\'s heritage. He adds that his father was a good listener and taught him how to play the piano. He says his grandfather taught him to read and write. His father was very important to him, and his mother taught him piano.\n\nHis grandfather was very strict with him and he was very good at it. His mother is very religious, and it is her opinion that people should not be allowed to sing or dance. She is very strict in her beliefs. Her father, who was very religious and very strict, died when Ken was a young man. He is very proud of him. Ken and his father are very close. They have a very close relationship.',NULL,NULL),(69440,196,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/s26cwr/November_19_2023_Across_the_Universeaqfej.mp3','2023-11-20 21:10:51',431961989,'2023-11-21 01:49:51','2023-11-20 23:05:37','The sound of your City fundraising campaign. The last day of On-Air Campaign. The Host of CIUT.fm announces that it is the final day of the campaign. He hopes listeners will come in and donate. He also invites listeners to listen more than they usually do.\n\nHe explains that the station is a unique, free, and open format and that he wants listeners to value what they hear on the station. He adds that they should call and donate at CIUT and listen to the music.\n\nThe Basement freaks are going to perform a track called \"Hit the Flame\" as they get to the end of the show. He asks listeners to call and give. He thanks all the listeners who have already donated. He then thanks Neil Pratt and Graham Benfield for their financial contribution.',NULL,NULL),(69441,257,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/ag49k5/November_16_2023_Psychedelic_Stoner_Rocka17bo.mp3','2023-11-20 21:12:49',287962512,'2023-11-21 01:50:47','2023-11-20 23:05:50','The next Thursday night program is heard, and the host is Lee Ronaldo\'s son, Sage. Ken says he\'s a huge fan of the program, and he tells us that it\'s going to be a big hit.\n\nHe also says that they\'re doing a big tour of the building during the fall fundraiser, and that they need your help. They\'re asking listeners to give them a call or go to their website, where they can donate.Ken then announces the program\'s start time. He starts off by playing the track \"Sergeant Taurus on Poke\" and then proceeds to play \"The Space Huns.\" Ken says they need the phone donation lines and the donation site to be really busy right now.',NULL,NULL),(69442,292,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/rcumdw/November_17_2023_The_Cool_Side_of_the_Pillow9gy4h.mp3','2023-11-20 21:08:44',287962512,'2023-11-21 01:51:52','2023-11-20 23:05:51','Lydia presents her program, \"The Cool Side of The Pillow,\"  every week and asks listeners to donate to the cause. Lydia herself has also come to the station to promote the program. The next program is a meditation program called \"Meditation Relaxation Chill,\" which was developed by Lydia after listening to Paul Horn\'s program in the Taj Mahal. The program has since evolved into the \"Cool Side of the pillow,\" which Lydia calls \"Moroccan spirit.\" The program will be expanded to include more music, and Lydia says that she is planning to add more \"lively\" music in the future.',NULL,NULL),(69443,81,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/20/The Sentinel’s Marvellous Kaleidoscope - November 20, 2023 at 15:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-20 15:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-20 23:30:44','2023-11-20 23:06:09','Part 1 of the Future of Progressive Fusion and Alternative Music series begins with a conversation between Nicholas Cooper, the creator of the Sound of Turtle Island, and the artist and curator of the series. He begins by stating that he wants to pay respect to Indigenous territories and local communities, as well as Black communities. He says that he would like to recognize that their music is being played on Turtle Island from treaty lands, and that many of the sounds are adaptations of Black culture. He also says that the majority in the music featured originated from Black culture, which was initially created under circumstances of oppression. He thanks the Black community for their contributions to the popular alternative of the Sentinels marvelous kaleidoscope',NULL,NULL),(69444,82,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/20/Big Sis Radio - November 20, 2023 at 17:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-20 17:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-21 01:54:03','2023-11-21 01:06:02','The narrator opens this show by talking about the Big Sis Radio show. The narrator explains that the show is from the treaty territories of the Mississauga-Credit Union. The show is a mix of music from the province of Alberta. He talks about the silent film, Sherlock Jr.\n\n, which was released in 1924. The silent film has some of the most famous stunts in the film, including one in which the window of a house is cut open by the side of it. The music for the show starts with Hay Major, an elegant rock band. It\'s one of Cece\'s favorite things to do. One of his favorite things about music is that it makes him feel infinite.',NULL,NULL),(69445,83,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/20/to know the land - November 20, 2023 at 18:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-20 18:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-21 01:46:35','2023-11-21 01:06:04','In this episode, Byron talks about his show, \"How we defend the land,\" which is a podcast about how people interact with and defend the natural world.Byron\'s name is Byron, and he has an affinity for storytelling about the land, whether it\'s through scientific journals, or through storytelling in first person, or storytelling in both first person and in the form of mythology.\n\nByron also talks about the importance of October, the time of year when people tend to spend a lot of time reading books and collecting things. He finds that the stories and folklore that he reads often trace back to pre-Christian traditions of direct relationship between humans and the land. He thinks that the origins of all life, all nourishment, and all things are often traced back to those traditions.\n\nByron thinks that in these stories, there are often interspecies communication, that the plants and animals can communicate with the humans, and sometimes there are wood-spirits or sea spirits, and that there is a different kind of way of looking about the world that he thinks especially in the western identities and Western notions, which become rationalistic and rationalistic, and also Christian. And often, we start looking toward often like indigenous practices or practices of connection with the',NULL,NULL),(69446,157,'https://mcdn.podbean.com/mf/web/uty6t4/509-33-45-78-nov20-23.mp3','2023-11-21 02:58:04',288228940,'2023-11-21 04:18:37','2023-11-21 03:05:21','The first song we hear is from Black and the King, a song written by Tom Wilson and Stephen Fury. This song is called \"Better When I\'m Stoned\" and it was released in 2003.\n\nThe song was originally recorded by the band The Searchers in the late \'50s and early \'60s. The band was called \"The Searchers\" after the 1956 movie \"TheSearchers\" and the band disbanded in March of 2019. The band\'s songs include Sex Pistols \"Not Your Steppin Stones\" and \"Squindle,\" John Mills \"Blues Breakers,\" Eddie Kirkland\'s \"Man of Stone,\" Mick Taylor\'s Crusade album, Sly and the Stone Family Stone, and Stoned Woman. The Stones \"Heart of Stone\" and Brian Jones\' \"Low Tune Guitar\" were the first songs we heard in the \'50\'s and the \'60\'s.\n\nManza \"B.B.\" Sisoko\'s song was also released in the \'60s and he was one of the featured artists on the guitar.',NULL,NULL),(69447,84,'https://archive.cfru.ca/archive/2023/11/20/Blues Around the Block - November 20, 2023 at 20:00 - CFRU 93.3.mp3','2023-11-20 20:00:00',86507648,'2023-11-21 03:51:55','2023-11-21 03:05:54','Mac Dee is the host of the show and he tells 